Preheat your #oven{} to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7.

Chop the @potatoes{450} lengthways into 1cm slices, then chop into 1cm wide
chips (no need to peel).

Pop them onto a large #baking tray{}. Drizzle with @oil{drizzle}, season with
@salt{for seasoning} and @pepper{for seasoning}, then toss to coat. Spread out
in a single layer.

> TIP: Use two baking trays if necessary.

When the oven is hot, bake on the top shelf until golden, ~{25-30%minutes}.
Halfway through, sprinkle the @hard Italian style cheese{20%g}(grated) over the
chips and toss, then return to the oven for the remaining time.

Meanwhile, slice the @brioche hot dog buns{2} top down through the middle (but
not all the way through).

Peel and grate the @garlic cloves{2}(grated with a garlic press or grated).
Grate the @mature cheddar cheese{60%g}.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{drizzle} in a large #frying pan{} on medium-high heat.

Once hot, lay in the @British streaky bacon{4%rashers} and fry until crispy and
brown, ~{3-4%minutes} on each side. Transfer to a #plate{} lined with kitchen
paper.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw meat. Cook bacon
> thoroughly.

Keep the bacon fat in the pan and pop back on medium-high heat.

Once hot, add the @British beef mince{240%g} and fry until browned,
~{5-6%minutes}. Use a #spoon{} to break it up as it cooks, then drain and
discard any excess fat.

Season with @salt{for seasoning} and @pepper{for seasoning}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw mince. It's
> cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Add the garlic and @Cajun spice mix{1%tbsp} to the beef. Cook for ~{30%seconds}.

Stir in the @tomato passata{1%jar}, @red wine jus paste{15%g}, @sugar{1} and
@water{100%ml} for the sauce (see pantry for both amounts).

Bring to the boil, stirring, then turn the heat down slightly and simmer until
thickened, ~{7-8%minutes}. Taste and season with @salt{for seasoning} and
@pepper{for seasoning} if needed. Meanwhile, crumble the crispy bacon.

Pop the buns onto a baking tray and into the oven to warm through,
~{2-3%minutes}.

Switch your oven setting to grill and move the chips to the bottom shelf.

Remove the buns from the oven and spoon in as much chilli into each as you'd
like, then top with the cheese.

Grill until the cheese is melted and bubbling, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Just before everything's ready, toss the @baby leaf mix{50%g} with the
@balsamic glaze{12%ml} and a drizzle of @olive oil{drizzle}.

Place the Cajun flavoured chilli filled buns onto your plates and sprinkle over
the bacon crumble.

Serve the cheesy chips and salad alongside. Enjoy!